201306\n|-\n|[[Sidney Lowe]]||86\u201378||.524||2006\u201311\n|-\n|[[Mark Gottfried]]||123\u201386||.589||2011\u20132017\n|-\n|[[Kevin Keatts]]||45\u201324||.652||2017\u20132019\n|-\n|Total||1,731\u20131,061||.632||1911\u20132019\n|}\n\n==Notable former players==\nSee [[:Category:NC State Wolfpack men's basketball players]]\n\n==References==\n*{{cite book\n|author     = Chappelow, Craig\n|year       = 2002\n|title      = Raleigh's Reynolds Coliseum\n|pages      = \n|publisher  = Arcadia Publishing\n|isbn       = 0-7385-1441-1\n}}\n*{{cite book\n|author     = Grundy, Pamela\n|year       = 2000\n|title      = Learning to Win: Sports, Education, and Social Change in Twentieth-Century North Carolina\n|pages      = \n|publisher  = The University of North Carolina Press\n|isbn       = 0-8078-2619-7\n}}\n*{{cite book\n|author     = Menzer, Joe\n|year       = 2004\n|title      = Four Corners: How UNC, N.C. State, Duke, and Wake Forest Made North Carolina the Center of the Basketball Universe\n|pages      = \n|publisher  = University of Nebraska Press\n|isbn       = 0-8032-8300-8\n}}\n*{{cite book\n|author       = Golenbock, Peter\n|year       = 1990\n|title       = Personal Fouls \u2013 The Broken Promises and Shattered Dreams of Big Money Basketball at Jim Valvano's North Carolina State\n|pages       = [https://archive.org/details/personalfouls00pete/page/396 396]\n|publisher       = Penguin Group (USA) Incorporated\n|isbn       = 0-4511-6732-5\n|url-access       = registration\n|url       = https://archive.org/details/personalfouls00pete/page/396\n}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n\n{{NC State Wolfpack men's basketball navbox}}\n{{North Carolina State University}}\n{{Atlantic Coast Conference men's basketball navbox}}\n\n[[Category:NC State Wolfpack men's basketball| ]]\n", "name_user": "Triple 8~enwiki", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSteals:stat name", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NC_State_Wolfpack_men%27s_basketball"}
{"title_page": "Al Hibbler", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name            = Al Hibbler\n| image           = Alhibb.jpg\n| image_size    = \n| landscape     = \n| caption         = Al Hibbler in 1946\n| background    = solo_singer\n| birth_name    =  Albert (or Andrew) George Hibbler\n| birth_date      =  {{birth date|mf=yes|1915|08|16}}\n| birth_place     = [[Tyro, Mississippi|Tyro]], [[Mississippi]], U.S.\n| death_date = {{death date and age|2001|04|24|1915|08|16}}\n| death_place =  [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]]\n| genre = [[Traditional popular music]], [[jazz]], [[easy listening]]\n| occupation = Singer\n| years_active = 1935&ndash;2001\n| label = [[Norgran Records|Norgran]], [[Decca Records|Decca]], [[Reprise Records|Reprise]]\n| associated_acts = [[Duke Ellington]]\n}}\n\n'''Albert George Hibbler''' (August 16, 1915 &ndash; April 24, 2001) was an [[United States|American]] [[baritone]] vocalist, who sang with [[Duke Ellington]]'s orchestra before having several [[pop music|pop]] hits as a solo artist. Some of Hibbler's singing is classified as [[rhythm and blues]], but he is best seen as a bridge between R&B and [[traditional pop music]].<ref name=hibbleral>{{cite web |url=http://www.home.earthlink.net/~v1tiger/hibbler.html |title=Remembering al Hibbler |author=J.C. Marion |date=2004 |publisher=Home.earthlink.net\\accessdate=2015-08-17 |access-date=2007-08-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081010120713/http://home.earthlink.net/~v1tiger/hibbler.html |archive-date=2008-10-10 |url-status=dead }}</ref> According to one authority, \"Hibbler cannot be regarded as a [[jazz]] singer but as an exceptionally good interpreter of twentieth-century popular songs who happened to work with some of the best jazz musicians of the time.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oldies.com/artist-biography/Al-Hibbler.html |title=Colin Larkin, '&#39;The Encyclopedia of Popular Music'&#39;, excerpted at |publisher=Oldies.com |date= |accessdate=2013-06-10}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nHibbler was born in Tyro, [[Mississippi]], [[United States]], and was [[Blindness|blind]] from birth.<ref name=\"hibbleral\"/> Some sources give his birth name as Andrew George Hibbler.<ref name=\"bare\">{{cite book| first1= Bob| last1= Eagle| first2= Eric S.| last2= LeBlanc| year= 2013| title= Blues - A Regional Experience| publisher= Praeger Publishers| location= Santa Barbara| pages=222\u2013223 | isbn= 978-0313344237}}</ref> At the age of 12 he moved to [[Little Rock, Arkansas]], where he attended [[Arkansas School for the Blind]], joining the school [[choir]].<ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite news|first=Ben |last=Ratliff |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/04/27/arts/al-hibbler-a-singer-with-ellington-s-band-dies-at-85.html?pagewanted=1 |title=Obituary by Ben Ratliff, '&#39;New York Times'&#39; |publisher=Nytimes.com |date=2001-04-27 |accessdate=2013-06-10}}</ref><ref name=\"amg\">{{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p3109/biography |first=John |last=Bush }}</ref> Later he began working as a [[blues]] singer in local bands, failing his first audition for [[Duke Ellington]] in 1935.<ref name=\"independent\">[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/al-hibbler-729067.html] {{dead link|date=August 2015}}</ref> However, after winning an amateur talent contest in [[Memphis, Tennessee]], he was given his start with Dub Jenkins and his Playmates; Jenkins was a popular Memphis saxophonist and bandleader. He later joined a band led by [[Jay McShann]] in 1942, and the following year joined Ellington's orchestra, replacing [[Herb Jeffries]].<ref name=\"amg\"/>\n\n==Career==\nHe stayed with Ellington for almost eight years, and featured on a range of Ellington standards, including \"[[Do Nothin' Til You Hear From Me]]\", the words for which were written specifically for him and which reached # 6 on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[pop chart]] (and # 1 for eight weeks on the [[R&B chart|\"Harlem Hit Parade\"]]) in 1944, \"I Ain't Got Nothin' But the Blues,\" and \"[[I'm Just a Lucky So-and-So]]\". Although Hibbler's style was described as \"mannered\", \"over-stated\", and \"full of idiosyncrasies\" and \"bizarre vocal pyrotechnics\", he was also considered \"undoubtedly the best\" of Ellington's male vocalists.<ref name=\"nyt\"/><ref name=\"amg\"/><ref name=\"jazzhouse\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jazzhouse.org/gone/index.php3?view=988386343 |title=Al Hibbler at |publisher=Jazzhouse.org |date= |accessdate=2013-06-10}}</ref> While with Ellington, Hibbler won the ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]'' New Star Award in 1947 and the ''[[Down Beat]]'' award for Best Band Vocalist in 1949.<ref name=\"independent\"/>\n\nHibbler left Ellington's band in 1951 after a dispute over his wages. He then recorded with various bands including those of [[Johnny Hodges]] and [[Count Basie]], and for various labels including [[Mercury Records|Mercury]] and Norgran, a subsidiary of [[Verve Records]], for whom he released an [[LP album|LP]], ''Al Hibbler Favorites'', in 1953.<ref name=discography>[http://www.mossiehigh.com/Al_Hibbler/1953.html]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090825195711/http://www.mossiehigh.com/Al_Hibbler/1953.html |date=August 25, 2009 }}</ref>  In 1954 he released a more successful album, ''Al Hibbler Sings Duke Ellington'', and in [[1955 in music|1955]], he started recording with [[Decca Records]], with immediate success. His biggest hit was \"[[Unchained Melody]]\",<ref name=pc17>{{Gilliland |url=https://digital.library.unt.edu/ark:/67531/metadc19767/m1/ |title=Show 17 - The Soul Reformation: More on the evolution of rhythm and blues. [Part 3&#93;  |date=2013-05-28 |accessdate=2013-06-10}}</ref> which reached # 3 on the US pop chart, sold over one million copies, and was awarded a [[music recording sales certification|gold disc]].<ref name=\"The Book of Golden Discs\">{{cite book\n| first= Joseph\n| last= Murrells\n| year= 1978\n| title= The Book of Golden Discs\n| edition= 2nd\n| publisher= Barrie and Jenkins Ltd\n| location= London\n| page= [https://archive.org/details/bookofgoldendisc00murr/page/74 74]\n| isbn= 0-214-20512-6\n| url= https://archive.org/details/bookofgoldendisc00murr/page/74\n}}</ref> Hibbler's version also reached # 2 in the United Kingdom, becoming his only British chart success. Its success led to network appearances, including a live [[big band remote|jazz club remote]] on NBC's ''[[Monitor (NBC Radio)|Monitor]]''. Other hits were \"[[He (song)|He]]\" ([[1955 in music|1955]]),<ref name=pc17/> \"11th Hour Melody\" and \"Never Turn Back\" (both in [[1956 in music|1956]]). \"[[After the Lights Go Down Low (song)|After the Lights Go Down Low]]\" (also in 1956) was his last [[top 40|top ten]] hit.<ref name=\"amg\"/>\n\n===Activism===\nIn the late 1950s and 1960s, Hibbler became a [[civil rights]] activist, marching with protestors and getting arrested in 1959 in [[New Jersey]] and in 1963 in [[Alabama]]. The notoriety of this activism discouraged major [[record label]]s from carrying his work, but [[Frank Sinatra]] supported him and signed him to a contract with his label, [[Reprise Records]].<ref name=\"nyt\"/> However, Hibbler made very few recordings after that, occasionally doing live appearances through the 1990s. In 1971, Hibbler sang two songs at [[Louis Armstrong]]'s funeral.<ref>John A. Drobnicki, \"Hibbler, Albert George ('Al'),\" in ''The Scribner Encyclopedia of American Lives,'' Vol. VI: ''2000-2002'' (Scribner's, 2004), p. 232.</ref> In 1972 he made an album, ''[[A Meeting of the Times]]'', with another fiercely independent blind musician, the multi-instrumentalist [[Rahsaan Roland Kirk]].<ref name=\"independent\"/>\n\n==Death and legacy==\nHe died at [[Holy Cross Hospital (Chicago)|Holy Cross Hospital]] in [[Chicago]] in 2001, at the age of 85.<ref name=\"hibbleral\"/><ref name=\"nyt\"/> He is buried at Lincoln Cemetery in [[Blue Island, Illinois]].\n\nOn June 25, 2019, ''[[The New York Times Magazine]]'' listed Al Hibbler among hundreds of artists whose material was reportedly destroyed in the [[2008 Universal fire]].<ref name=\"Rosen2\">{{cite web |last1=Rosen |first1=Jody |title=Here Are Hundreds More Artists Whose Tapes Were Destroyed in the UMG Fire |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/25/magazine/universal-music-fire-bands-list-umg.html |website=The New York Times |accessdate=June 28, 2019 |date=June 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Solo singles discography===\n{|class=wikitable\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Year\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Titles (A-side, B-side)<br /><small>Both sides from same album except where indicated</small>\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Label & number\n! colspan=\"3\"|Chart positions\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Album\n|-\n! <small>[[Billboard Hot 100|U.S. Pop]]<ref>{{cite book|first=Joel|last=Whitburn|year=2003|title=Top Pop Singles 1955-2002|edition=1st|publisher=Record Research Inc.|location=Menomonee Falls, Wisconsin|isbn=0-89820-155-1|page=[https://archive.org/details/joelwhitburnstop00whitbur/page/313 313]|url=https://archive.org/details/joelwhitburnstop00whitbur/page/313}}</ref></small>\n! <small>[[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs|U.S. R&B]]<ref name=\"whitburnr&b\">{{cite book |title= Top R&B/Hip-Hop Singles: 1942-2004|last=Whitburn |first=Joel |authorlink=Joel Whitburn |year=2004 |publisher=Record Research |page=191}}</ref></small>\n! <small>[[UK Singles Chart|UK]]<ref name=\"betts\">{{cite book| first= Graham| last= Betts| year=2004| title= Complete UK Hit Singles 1952-2004| edition= 1st|publisher= Collins| location= London| isbn= 0-00-717931-6| page=355}}</ref> </small>\n|-\n| 1946\n| align=\"left\"|\"[[I Got It Bad (and That Ain't Good)]]\"<br /><small>b/w \"How Long Blues\"</small>\n| Aladdin 154\n| <center>-</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n| align=\"left\" rowspan=\"3\"|''I Surrender Dear''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|1947\n| align=\"left\"|\"S'posin'\"<br /><small>b/w \"[[Don't Take Your Love from Me]]\"</small>\n| Aladdin 155A - 156A\n| <center>-</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n|-\n| align=\"left\"|\"[[I Surrender Dear]]\"<br /><small>b/w \"Fat and Forty\"</small>\n| Aladdin 155B - 156B\n| <center>-</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|1948\n| align=\"left\"|\"[[Trees (poem)|Trees]]\" / \n| rowspan=\"2\"|Miracle 501\n| <center>-</center>\n| <center>2</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n| align=\"left\" rowspan=\"2\"|''Melodies by Al Hibbler''\n|-\n| align=\"left\"|\"[[Lover, Come Back to Me|Lover, Come Back To Me]]\" \n| <center>-</center>\n| <center>9</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n|-\n| 1950\n| align=\"left\"|\"[[Danny Boy]]\"<br /><small>b/w \"Song of the Wanderer\" (from ''After the Lights Go Down Low'')</small>\n| Atlantic 911\n| <center>-</center>\n| <center>9</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n| align=\"left\"|Non-album track\n|-\n| rowspan=\"7\"|1951\n| align=\"left\"|\"The Blues Come Falling Down\"<br /><small>B/w \"[[Old Folks (1938 song)|Old Folks]]\" (Non-album track)</small>\n| Atlantic 925\n| <center>-</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n| align=\"left\" rowspan=\"3\"|''[[After the Lights Go Down Low]]''\n|-\n| align=\"left\"|\"[[Trav'lin' Light (song)|Travelin' Light]]\"<br /><small>b/w \"If I Knew You Were There\"</small>\n| Atlantic 932\n| <center>-</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n|-\n| align=\"left\"|\"Now I Lay Me Down to Dream\"<br /><small>b/w \"This Is Always\"</small>\n| Atlantic 945\n| <center>-</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n|-\n| align=\"left\"|\"What Will I Tell My Heart\"<br /><small>b/w \"[[It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing)|It Don't Mean a Thing]]\"</small>\n| Chess 1455\n| <center>-</center>\n| <center>9</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n| align=\"left\" rowspan=\"4\"|''Melodies by Al Hibbler''\n|-\n| align=\"left\"|\"Trees\"<br /><small>b/w \"Lover Come Back to Me\"</small>\n| Chess 1456\n| <center>-</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n|-\n| align=\"left\"|\"[[(In My) Solitude|Solitude]]\"<br /><small>b/w \"Feather Roll Blues\"</small>\n| Chess 1457\n| <center>-</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n|-\n| align=\"left\"|\"My Little Brown Book\"<br /><small>b/w \"I Love You\"</small>\n| Chess 1481\n| <center>-</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n|-\n| 1952\n| align=\"left\"|\"Please\"<br /><small>b/w \"Believe It Beloved\"</small>\n| Mercury 89011\n| <center>-</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n| align=\"left\"|''Al Hibbler Sings Love Songs''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|1953\n| align=\"left\"|\"Sent for You Yesterday and Here You Come Today\"<br /><small>b/w \"Goin' to Chicago\"</small>\n| Mercury 89028\n| <center>-</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n| align=\"left\"|''Basie Jazz''\n|-\n| align=\"left\"|\"[[There Is No Greater Love]]\"<br /><small>b/w \"It Must Be True\"</small>\n| Mercury 89046\n| <center>-</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n| align=\"left\" rowspan=\"2\"|''Al Hibbler Sings Love Songs''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"|1954\n| align=\"left\"|\"[[As Time Goes By (song)|As Time Goes By]]\"<br /><small>b/w \"[[I'm Getting Sentimental Over You]]\"</small>\n| Clef 89095\n| <center>-</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n|-\n| align=\"left\"|\"[[Poor Butterfly]]\"<br /><small>b/w \"Fat and Forty\"</small>\n| Chess 1569\n| <center>-</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n| align=\"left\"|''Melodies By Al Hibbler''\n|-\n| align=\"left\"|\"Little Brown Book\"<br /><small>b/w \"[[I'm Just a Lucky So-and-So]]\"</small>\n| Norgran 114\n| <center>-</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n| align=\"left\"|''Al Hibbler Sings Love Songs''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"6\"|1955\n| align=\"left\"|\"After the Lights Go Down Low\"<small> (Original version)</small><br /><small>b/w \"Tell Me\"</small>\n| Original 1006\n| <center>-</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n| align=\"left\"|''After the Lights Go Down Low''\n|-\n| align=\"left\"|\"[[Unchained Melody]]\"<br /><small>b/w \"Daybreak\"</small>\n| Decca 29441 (US)<br/>Brunswick 05420 (UK)\n| <center>3</center>\n| <center>1</center>\n| <center>2<ref>The record reached #1 in the rival [[List of Record Mirror number-one singles (UK)|''Record Mirror'' singles chart]].</ref></center>\n| align=\"left\" rowspan=\"2\"|''Hits by Hibbler''\n|-\n| align=\"left\"|\"They Say You're Laughing at Me\"<br /><small>b/w \"I Can't Put My Arms Around a Memory\" (Non-album track)</small>\n| Decca 29543\n| <center>-</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n|-\n| align=\"left\"|\"Danny Boy\"<br /><small>b/w \"Now I Lay Me Down to Dream\" (from ''After the Lights Go Down Low'')</small>\n| Atlantic 1071\n| <center>-</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n| align=\"left\"|Non-album track\n|-\n| align=\"left\"|\"He\"<br /><small>b/w \"Breeze (Blow My Baby Back to Me)\"</small>\n| Decca 29660\n| <center>4</center>\n| <center>13</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n| align=\"left\"|''Hits by Hibbler''\n|-\n| align=\"left\"|\"[[This Love of Mine]]\"<br /><small>b/w \"Every Hour on the Hour\" (from ''Al Hibbler Sings Love Songs'')</small>\n| Norgran 143\n| <center>-</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n| align=\"left\"|Non-album track\n|-\n| rowspan=\"7\"|1956\n| align=\"left\"|\"11th Hour Melody\"<br /><small>b/w \"Let's Try Again\"</small>\n| Decca 29789\n| <center>21</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n| align=\"left\"|''Hits by Hibbler''\n|-\n| align=\"left\"|\"Never Turn Back\" /\n| rowspan=\"2\"|Decca 29950\n| <center>22</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n| align=\"left\" rowspan=\"2\"|Non-album tracks\n|-\n| align=\"left\"|\"Away All Boats\"\n| <center>77</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n| <center>-</center>\n|-\n| align=\"left\"|\"After the Lights Go Down Low\"<small> (re-recording)</small><br /><small>b/w \"I Was Telling Her Ab